1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4
{Objectively, this is not a very challenging variation. Nevertheless,
superficially, it looks the most natural one (and logical quite popular at
club or experimental level). That is why we need to investigate. Exchanging
the bishop so early frees Black's play and slightly weakens White's kingside.
Besides, our move order is designed precisely for such lines. Since our pawn
remains on d7, we can prevent possible problems due to the weakness of the
c6-square. If White plays b2-b3 followed by Bb2, the play transposes to a
position which is dealt with in the first database. In this chapter, we will
examine only independent lines.} Bxg2 9. Kxg2 Qc7 ({Mihai Suba's game inserted
below actually went through the move order} 9... Qc8 {transposing to the main
line after a slightly later ...Qb7. Since there is no danger of Nb5 or Nd5, I
do not quite understand the need for such a contorted development. Here is
just a game where the queen proved less effective on c8 than on c7:} 10. Qd3
Nc6 11. b3 (11. Nxc6 Qxc6+ {transposes below.}) 11... Ne5 12. Qe3 $5 {A
provocative move, probably inspirred by the fact that unlike after ...Qc7 the
e5-knight is hanging.} Nfg4 ({Actually, Black could return to the normal paths
with} 12... Qb7+ 13. Kg1 Ng6 14. Bb2 h5 15. h4 Be7 16. Rad1 O-O {with similar
play as in the main line, only that the white queen is not especially well
placed on e3.}) 13. Qd2 Bb4 14. Bb2 O-O 15. f3 Nf6 16. Nc2 Ba5 17. Qe3 d6 18.
Ne4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 b5 20. c5 $16 {Karpov,A (2644)-Topalov,V (2813) Zuerich 2009
(½-½, 37)}) 10. Qd3 (10. b3 Be7 11. Bb2 {is an exact transposition to
chapter 2 and 3.}) (10. Bg5 Be7 (10... Qxc4 11. Rc1 $16) 11. Rc1 Nc6 $11 {
is inoffensive as the bishop is not very mobile on g5.} 12. Nd5 $2 exd5 13.
Bxf6 Bxf6 14. cxd5 Bxd4 $19) (10. Qa4 $6 Be7 11. f3 O-O 12. Bf4 Qb7 {leads to
a Queen's Indian tabyia (4.g3 Ba6 5.Qa4 Bb7 followed by ...c7-c5) but with an
extra tempo for Black. Even the QI line is OK for him, as the queen does not
stand well on a4, but with an extra tempo Black even has chances to take over
the initiative.}) 10... Nc6 11. b3 (11. Nxc6 Qxc6+ {is likely to cause White
problems with his c-pawn.} 12. f3 (12. Qf3 Rc8 13. Bg5 Qxf3+ 14. Kxf3 Rxc4 15.
Rfc1 Rc6 $17 {Carton,P (2240)-Suba,M (2505) Blackpool 1990 (0-1, 40)}) 12...
Rc8 13. Be3 (13. b3 d5 $17) 13... Qxc4 14. Qxc4 Rxc4 15. Bxb6 Bb4 $11 {Richter,
C (2369)-Stangl,M (2438) Germany 2015 (½-½, 24)}) 11... Ne5 ({It is most
natural to start this counterplay at once, but Black can also delay it for one
move:} 11... Be7 12. Bb2 Ne5 13. Qd2 Qb7+ 14. f3 O-O (14... h5 15. h4 O-O $11)
15. Rad1 Rfd8 16. e4 Rac8 17. Rfe1 Bf8 18. Qe2 d6 19. f4 Ned7 20. Qf3 Nc5 21.
g4 g6 22. g5 Nh5 23. f5 Re8 {Black has stabilized the position and can look
forward into the future with confidence.} 24. fxe6 $6 ({Probably White feared
plans based on ...b6-b5 combined with ...exf5 or simply ...exf5 followed by ...
Nf4. But releasing the tension is a concession.} 24. Kg1 {is more consistent
even though after} Nd7 {followed by ...Ne5 Black would be ready to carry out
the aforementioned pawn breaks soon.}) 24... fxe6 25. Rf1 Qe7 $15 {Gurieli,N 
(2340)-Suba,M (2505) London 1990 (0-1, 41)}) 12. Qd2 (12. Qe3 {makes less
sense with the e5-knight defended.} h5 13. h3 {Trinh,B (2089)-Hebert,J (2444)
Repentigny 2008 (0-1, 26)} h4 14. g4 Bc5 15. Rd1 Ng6 16. Qf3 O-O 17. Be3 Rac8
$132) (12. Qc2 {does not change the character of the game too much:} Rc8 13.
Bb2 {Spindelboeck,G (2200)-Wojtkiewicz,A (2570) Vienna 1995 (0-1, 41)} h5 14.
h4 Be7 15. e4 O-O 16. Rac1 Ng6 $11) 12... Qb7+ 13. Kg1 h5 $1 14. h4 {After
having provoked h2-h4, Black has increased the stability of his knights, as
f2-f4 would chronically weaken the g4-square.} (14. Bb2 h4 $17 {puts the king
in a lethal danger.}) 14... Be7 15. a4 O-O 16. Ba3 $6 {This loses too much
time.} (16. Bb2 Rfd8 17. Rad1 Rac8 $11 {would offer Black a comfortable play,
as he soon he will open the centre with ...d6-d5. By the way, he could have
done this also by one or two moves earlier.}) 16... Bxa3 17. Rxa3 Rfd8 18. a5
$2 ({It was not late to retain a viable position by bringing the rook back
into play:} 18. Raa1 d5) 18... d5 19. Qg5 Neg4 20. cxd5 Nxd5 21. Qxh5 Nxc3 22.
Qxg4 Rxd4 $1 {0-1 Roibas Alonso,D-Suba,M (2520) Oviedo 1992} *

