1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. b3 Be7 8. Bb2
O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qc7 12. e4 d6 ({Given the chosen move
order, the almost never played} 12... Nc6 {is worth mentioning. If White
reacts neutrally this could transpose below.} 13. Nxc6 (13. Rc1 Nxd4 14. Qxd4
d6 $11) 13... dxc6 (13... Qxc6 14. Qe2 d6 {would be also typical for the lines
below.}) 14. f4 Rad8 15. Qe2 e5 16. fxe5 Nd7 17. e6 fxe6 18. Qg4 Bf6 19. Qxe6+
Kh8 20. Qg4 Nc5 $44 {with great piece activity for the pawn.}) 13. Qe2 ({
The relatively rare} 13. Rc1 {prevents the immediate ...Nc6.} Qb7 (13... Nc6 $2
14. Nd5 $18) 14. f3 Rc8 ({As in most of the lines below Black can also play
with all knights on board, as after e2-e4 the invasion on c6 is not an issue.} 
14... Nbd7 15. Qe2 Rfe8 16. Rfd1 Rad8 17. Nc2 Bf8 18. Ne3 Nc5 19. Rc2 Rb8 20.
b4 Ncd7 21. Nb1 Rbc8 22. Nd2 Rc7 23. Nb3 Rec8 24. a3 Qb8 $11 {Taimanov,M (2424)
-Portisch,L (2555) Moscow 1999 (½-½, 31)}) 15. Qe2 Nbd7 ({Simpler is} 15...
Nc6 16. Nxc6 Rxc6 $11 {followed by ...Rac8.}) 16. Rfd1 Rc7 17. Nc2 Ne5 {
Black is playing rather provocatively.} 18. Nd4 Rac8 19. h3 Bf8 20. Kh2 Nfd7
21. f4 Nc6 22. Nf3 Re8 23. Rd2 (23. Ba3 Nc5 24. b4 Nd7 25. b5 $16) 23... Na7
24. e5 dxe5 25. fxe5 Bb4 26. Rd4 Nc6 27. Rg4 {Buchholz,M (2235)-Spraggett,K 
(2450) Montreal 1981 (½-½, 52)} f5 28. exf6 Nxf6 $11) (13. f3 Nc6 14. Nxc6
Qxc6 15. Qe2 Rfd8 ({Or else} 15... Rab8 16. Rac1 Rfd8 17. Nd1 b5 $11 {½-½
Padevsky,N (2455)-Rajkovic,D (2490) Smederevska Palanka 1978}) 16. Rfd1 Ne8 ({
I would prefer keeping the knight active with} 16... Nd7 17. Rac1 Rac8 18. Rc2
Bf6 $11) 17. a4 Bf6 18. Rd3 Ra7 19. Rad1 Rad7 20. Qd2 h6 21. Ne2 Bxb2 22. Qxb2
{½-½ Uhlmann,W (2530)-Vogt,L (2500) Berlin East 1979}) (13. f4 {is
double-edged as it weakens e4.} Nc6 14. Nf3 Qb7 (14... b5 $5 15. cxb5 axb5 16.
Nxb5 Qb6 17. Nc3 $2 Ng4 $17) 15. Qe2 Rfe8 16. Rad1 b5 17. e5 dxe5 18. fxe5 Nd7
19. Ne4 bxc4 20. bxc4 {Bronstein,D (2495)-Kalinitschew,S (2320) Moscow 1982 
(1-0, 31)} Rad8 21. Nd6 Bxd6 22. exd6 e5 $13) 13... Re8 {Again Black has
several plans and move orders available:} (13... Nc6 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 15. f3 Rab8
16. Rac1 Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Qa7 18. Rcd1 Rdc8 (18... b5 $5 19. cxb5 axb5 20. a3 Ne8
21. Nxb5 Qa6 22. a4 Nc7 $11) 19. a4 Nd7 20. Ba1 Qc7 21. f4 Rd8 22. Qg4 {
Veingold,A (2430)-Suba,M (2535) Tallinn 1983 (½-½, 37)} Nc5 23. Rb1 Bf6 24.
Rdd1 Qb7 $17 {White's structure is rather vulnerable.}) (13... Qb7 14. f3 Rc8
15. Rfd1 Nc6 16. Nxc6 Rxc6 17. Rd2 Rac8 {This was a last round game in which
Black needed to win in order to keep chances for qualifying for the Candidates
matches. But his strong opponent managed to maintain equality and qualified
himself.} 18. Nd1 b5 19. Ne3 Ne8 20. Rad1 Bg5 21. f4 Bd8 22. Qf3 Ba5 23. Rf2
Bb6 24. Bd4 h6 25. Bxb6 Rxb6 26. Rfd2 Rbc6 27. e5 Qb8 28. exd6 Rxd6 29. f5
Rxd2+ 30. Rxd2 Nf6 31. fxe6 fxe6 $11 {Polugaevsky,L (2625)-Gheorghiu,F (2540)
Riga 1979 (½-½, 48)}) 14. f3 (14. Rac1 Nbd7 (14... Nc6 {is possible now since
} 15. Nd5 $2 {does not work:} exd5 16. cxd5 Nxd4 $19) 15. Rfd1 Bf8 16. f3 Rac8
17. Nc2 Qb8 18. Ne3 Rc7 19. Rd2 Rec8 20. Rdc2 {Ionescu,C-Boensch,U (2365)
Bucharest 1976 (0-1, 60) With mutual but fairly equal chances.}) 14... Nbd7 (
14... Nc6 $5) 15. Rad1 Bf8 16. Rfe1 Qb7 17. Rd2 Rac8 18. Nc2 Rc7 19. Ba3 Nc5
20. Red1 Rec8 {White is perfectly regrouped and can look into the future with
optimism, Kestler,H (2405)-Ribli,Z (2590) Baden-Baden 1981 (0-1, 40)} *

