1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. b3 Be7 8. Bb2
O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qc7 12. e3 $5 {Even though this looks
less ambitious than 12.e4, it is not without venom. White hopes to use the
weakness of the c6-square with Qf3, but Black is not in a hurry to play ...
d7-d6.} Nc6 $1 {White's plan is revealed in the following lines:} (12... Qb7+
13. Qf3 Qxf3+ 14. Kxf3 d6 15. g4 Rc8 {Stojanovic,M (2552)-Perunovic,M (2589)
Subotica 2008 (½-½, 16)} 16. g5 Nfd7 17. h4 $14) (12... d6 13. Qf3 Ra7 (13...
Nbd7 14. Nc6 $11) 14. Rfd1 Rc8 15. Rac1 Bf8 {Kortschnoj,V (2600)-Portisch,L 
(2620) Bad Kissingen 1983 (1-0, 57)} 16. g4 $36) 13. Nxc6 {Otherwise Black
will most likely carry out ...b6-b5 under favourable circumstances:} (13. Qf3 {
Szucs,V (2161)-Petenyi,T (2196) Slovakia 2008 (0-1, 29)} Nxd4 14. exd4 b5 15.
cxb5 axb5 16. Nxb5 Qc2 17. Rfb1 Rxa2 $1 $11) (13. f4 b5 14. cxb5 Nxd4 15. Qxd4
axb5 $15 {Pushkov,N (2302)-Rooze,J (2311) Eretria 2015 (0-1, 34)}) (13. Rc1 b5
$146 (13... Nxd4 14. exd4 b5 $11) 14. Nd5 exd5 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Nxc6 dxc6 (
16... Nxe3+ 17. fxe3 dxc6 18. Qg4 g6 19. Qd4 f6 20. Qd5+ cxd5 21. Rxc7 Rf7 22.
Rd7 $11) 17. Qxd5 c5 $11) 13... Qxc6+ 14. Qf3 Rfc8 {This speaks about Black's
intention to play for a win.} (14... b5 {is possible but leads to plain
equality after the queen exchange on c6.} 15. cxb5 axb5 16. a4 {Twardowski,L 
(2230)-Pisulinski,J (2385) Krynica 1997 (0-1, 40)} Qxf3+ 17. Kxf3 bxa4 18. bxa4
d5 $11 19. a5 $6 Rfb8 20. Ra2 Ra6 21. Rfa1 Bd8 $15) 15. a4 (15. Qxc6 Rxc6 {
does not change the essence of the position.} 16. Rfc1 (16. a4 d6 17. Rfd1 Kf8
18. Rab1 Nd7 19. Kf3 Nc5 20. Ba3 Ke8 21. Ke2 Rac8 22. Bb4 Nb7 23. Na2 b5 24.
axb5 axb5 25. cxb5 Rb6 26. Bd2 Rxb5 $11 {Negulescu,A-Suba,M (2435) Bucharest
1979 (½-½, 40)}) 16... h5 17. h3 d6 18. f4 Rb8 19. Kf3 Nd7 (19... b5 20. cxb5
axb5 21. Nd5 $1) 20. g4 Nc5 21. Rd1 b5 22. cxb5 axb5 23. Rac1 b4 24. Ne4 Ra6
25. Nxc5 hxg4+ 26. hxg4 dxc5 $11 {Antunes,A (2425)-Suba,M (2520) Seville 1993 
(½-½, 62) The pawn on a2 is weaker than that on c5, compensating for White's
more active bishop and kingside space advantage.}) 15... Rab8 {Black is
perfectly regrouped and can start the usual maneouvring phase.} (15... d6 {
may just transpose.} 16. Ne2 Ne4 17. Nd4 Qb7 18. Rfd1 Rc5 19. Rac1 Rac8 20. Kg1
h5 21. h4 g6 22. Qg2 R5c7 $11 23. Ba1 $2 d5 $15 {Kirov,N (2445)-Suba,M (2545)
Graz 1987 (0-1, 39)}) 16. Rfd1 d6 (16... h6 {is useful but not absolutely
necessary at this height of the game. But it still offers Black viable play:}
17. Rac1 d6 18. Ba3 Nd7 19. Rc2 Qxf3+ 20. Kxf3 Nc5 21. Rb1 f5 22. Ke2 Kf7 23.
Rcc1 g5 24. Rd1 Bf6 25. Bb4 Ke7 26. Rd2 g4 27. Rbd1 Bxc3 28. Bxc3 Ne4 29. Rc2
b5 30. axb5 axb5 31. Ra1 e5 $17 {Oms Pallisse,J-Marin,M (2515) Barcelona 1993 
(0-1, 44) White's careless play ahs allowed Black setting up a perfect
blockade on light squares.}) 17. Rab1 Kf8 ({Or similarly} 17... Nd7 18. Ba3 Nc5
19. Qxc6 Rxc6 20. Ne2 Rc7 21. Nd4 g6 22. Kf1 Bf8 23. f3 Re8 24. Kf2 f5 25. Ne2
Rb8 26. Nd4 Kf7 {With very pleasant play for Black in Vidarte Morales,A (2350)
-Marin,M (2545) Sitges 1996 (½-½, 57)}) 18. h3 Nd7 19. Qxc6 Rxc6 20. Ne2 Rc7
21. Ba3 Nc5 22. Nc3 f5 23. g4 g6 24. f4 Kf7 25. g5 h6 26. h4 Rh8 {Skalkotas,N 
(2150)-Suba,M (2341) Katerini 2014 (0-1, 65) with chances to harass White on
both wings.} *

