1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. b3 Be7 8. d4
cxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 10. Ba3 {A tricky way of tying to take advantage of Black's
move order. The pressure on d6 becomes threatening.} Nc6 $5 {This leads to
very original play.} (10... O-O 11. Rfd1 Nc6 12. Qf4 d5 {is likely to leave
Black very passive despite the almost symmetrical structure. I once enjoyed
playing this with white:} 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Ne5 Qb8 15. cxd5 Nexd5 16. Nxd5
Bxd5 17. e4 Bb7 18. Rac1 h6 19. Bf3 Ra7 20. Nd7 Nxd7 21. Rxd7 e5 22. Qf5 $16 {
Marin,M (2530)-Annageldyev,O (2490) Yerevan 1996 (1-0, 39)}) 11. Qf4 (11. Qd2 {
is more passive and less challenging.} Qc7 12. Rac1 Na7 {Now and in the main
line this is the start of a long knight regrouping.} 13. Rfd1 Rd8 14. Qf4 {
Basically losing a tempo.} O-O 15. Nd2 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Rd7 17. Nde4 Rfd8 18. Kg1
(18. Nxf6+ $11) 18... Ne8 $1 {A familiar issue.} 19. Ng5 Bf8 20. Bb2 h6 21. Nf3
Qb7 22. g4 g6 23. Ne4 e5 24. Qe3 Bg7 25. g5 h5 26. Nc3 b5 27. Nd5 Nc8 28. Nd2
Ne7 29. Ne4 bxc4 30. Nxe7+ Rxe7 31. Rxc4 d5 $15 {Cuadras Jorge-Suba,M/It,
Roses 1992/ (0-1, 48)}) 11... Qc7 12. Rfd1 Rd8 13. Rac1 Na7 {A familiar move
already.} 14. e4 ({As above the bishops' exchange frees Black's play.} 14. Ng5
Bxg2 15. Kxg2 O-O 16. Nge4 Ne8 $1 17. f3 {( with the idea Nf2)} (17. Rd2 $6 Qb7
18. Qf3 $2 d5 19. Bxe7 dxe4 20. Nxe4 Qxe7 $19) 17... Qb8 18. Bb2 Qb7 19. Nf2 b5
20. cxb5 (20. c5 d5 $1 $15 {with the idea: Nc6, Nf6, e5, Qf4}) 20... axb5 $11 {
Szuhanek,R (2355)-Marin,M (2520)/Romania tch 1995 (0-1, 48)}) (14. Na4 {
1-0 (40) Konopka,M (2415)-Kunz,K (2260) Augsburg 1997} Qb8 (14... Nc8 15. c5)
15. Qe3 b5) 14... O-O 15. Qe3 Nc8 {Over defending not only b6 and d6 but also
the bishop thus preparing the next move.} (15... Nd7 16. e5 $5 Nc5 17. b4 Nd7
18. exd6 Bxd6 19. Ne4 Be7 20. Nd4 {Gelfand,B (2675)-Karpov,A (2725)/Cap D'Agde
(rapid) 1998 (0-1, 44)} Nf6 $11) 16. Nd4 Qb8 17. Qe2 Rfe8 18. Bb2 Bf8 {Black
has completed the first part of his regrouping and only needs to activate the
reserve knight.} 19. Rd2 Ne7 20. f4 Ng6 {I played this almost without
considering the alternatives, but apparently there were even simpler ways to
clear equality:} (20... Qa8 $5 21. Rf1 Nc6 $5 $11) (20... e5 $5 21. fxe5 dxe5
22. Nc2 b5 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 $11 24. cxb5 $6 axb5 25. Qxb5 $2 Rd2 $19) 21. Rf1 $1
Qa8 22. Nc2 $6 (22. Kh1 $2 e5 $1 23. fxe5 dxe5 24. Nf3 (24. Nc2 Rxd2 25. Qxd2
Nxe4) 24... Nxe4 $17) (22. Rdd1 $5 {prevents the central break but Black could
continue his plan with} h5 $5) 22... d5 $1 {Everything is prepared for this
thematic break.} 23. e5 $6 (23. cxd5 exd5 24. e5 Bc5+ 25. Nd4 (25. Kh1 d4 26.
Na4 d3 $1) 25... Ne4 26. Nxe4 dxe4 27. Kh1 Ne7 $15) 23... Bc5+ 24. Kh1 (24. Nd4
dxc4 $15) 24... dxc4 (24... d4 25. Nxd4 $1) 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Ne1 Ng4 $1 $19 {
Bischoff,K (2550)-Marin,M (2545)/Calcutta op 1997 (0-1, 34) With decisive
initiative.} *

