1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. b3 Be7 8. Bb2
O-O 9. e3 $5 {This is aimed at keeping Black under doubt whether White will
later play Nxd4 or exd4. At the same time e2-e3 is not very useful if Black
keeps the tension in the centre.} d6 (9... Qc7 {is also playable but I prefer
the main line:} 10. d4 cxd4 11. exd4 d5 (11... d6 $5 {followed by ...Nbd7,
Rfe8 gives Black a somewhat passive but solid and flexible position.}) 12. cxd5
Nxd5 13. Rc1 Qd8 {With just some white pressure, Blatny,P (2555)-Atlas,V (2455)
Austria 1997 (1-0, 56) But basically this is not what Black wants when playing
the Hedgehog.}) 10. d4 Nbd7 11. d5 {The critical continuation. Otherwise Black
may just play ...Ne4 freeing his play.} (11. Qe2 Ne4 12. Nxe4 (12. Rad1 Nxc3
13. Bxc3 Be4 14. Ne1 Bxg2 15. Nxg2 cxd4 16. Bxd4 Qc7 17. Nf4 Ne5 18. Nh5 g6 19.
Nf4 b5 $11 {Dubov,D (2659)-Lysyj,I (2677) Sochi 2015 (½-½, 30)}) (12. Rfd1
Qb8 {Very provocative, but in the end inspired.} 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Ne5 Bxg2 15.
Nxd7 Qb7 16. Nxf8 Bf3 17. Qd3 Rxf8 {The bishop is not weaker than a rook now
and a former World champion did not find adequate defences against a the still
future one.} 18. Rd2 f5 19. Re1 Qc8 20. Qc3 Rf6 21. a3 Qe8 $19 22. dxc5 Qh5 23.
h4 Qg4 24. Kh2 bxc5 25. Rh1 Rg6 26. Kg1 Bxh4 27. Qa5 h6 {0-1 Smyslov,V (2545)
-Kasparov,G (2625) Moscow 1981}) 12... Bxe4 13. Rfd1 Qc7 14. Ne1 Bxg2 15. Nxg2
Nf6 16. Rac1 cxd4 (16... Qb7 {Ehlvest,J (2600)-Portisch,L (2610) Reggio Emilia
1989 (½-½, 32)} 17. d5 exd5 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Rxd5 $16) 17. exd4 Rfe8 $11 {
After the minor piece exchanges White's space advantage is less relevant.}) (
11. Qd3 cxd4 12. exd4 ({Now and in the lines below} 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 {
deprives White from the quick plan with Qf3.}) 12... d5 $11) (11. Qc2 cxd4 12.
exd4 d5 $11) (11. Rc1 Ne4 12. Ne2 {This resource is not available after Qe2,
but it is not too dangerous either.} b5 13. Nd2 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qc7
16. e4 Bf6 $11) 11... exd5 12. Nh4 {The most promising plan.} (12. Ne1 b5 13.
Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 (14. cxd5 Bf6 15. Qd2 a5 16. Nd3 Nb6 17. e4 Re8 18. Rac1
Bxb2 19. Qxb2 b4 20. Rfe1 Ba6 $36 {Taimanov,M (2480)-Yudasin,L (2505)
Leningrad 1987 (1-0, 31)}) 14... Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Nb6 16. Qd3 bxc4 17. bxc4 d5 18.
cxd5 Qxd5 19. Qxd5 {½-½ Gorovets,A (2477)-Zhigalko,A (2589) Minsk 2013}) (12.
cxd5 {just leads to a comfortable Benoni for Black.} b5 13. Nh4 Re8 14. e4 Bf8
15. Re1 Nb6 {½-½ Radulov,I (2407)-Adrian,C (2407) Agneaux 2000}) 12... g6 (
12... Re8 {is likely to offer White the slightly better chances:} 13. Nf5 Bf8
14. Nxd5 Rb8 15. Nxf6+ (15. e4 g6 16. Nfe3 Nxe4) (15. Rc1 {Olafsson,H (2445)
-Burger,K (2305) New York 1984(1-0, 65)} Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Bxd5 17. Qxd5 Re6 18.
Rfd1 b5 $132 {The f5-knight is a bit far from the critical squares.}) 15...
