1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 ({Players using
the move order} 6... Be7 {can answer} 7. Re1 {with} d5 {or 7...Ne4, but this
leads to completely different structures, with the tendency of being
one-sidedly marginally better for White.}) 7. Re1 {The most dreaded system of
development which aims for rapid space gaining. But if Black repels the first
wave of attack, White's position might become over-extended.} Be7 8. e4 d6 9.
d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Yg3g4,Yg4g5,Yc3d5] White's main plans are
f4-f5, possibly combined with g4-g5, while the typical Sicilian sacrifice Nd5
is always an issue. Black needs to choose his early move order with great care.
} Qc7 {Parrying the threat 11.e5 Bxg2 12.exf6!} 11. b3 ({For} 11. Be3 {see the
next few lines.}) 11... O-O (11... b5 $6 {is prematurely opening the queenside
with the development incomplete.} 12. Ba3 bxc4 13. Rc1 {[%cal Gc3a4] Planing
Na4 with an obvious queenside initiative.} Nbd7 14. Nd5 exd5 15. exd5 Ne5 16.
bxc4 {with tremenduous initiative for the piece.}) 12. Bb2 {This looks like a
very harmonious regrouping for White with both his bishops placed on the
longest available diagonals. But the b2-bishops has two knights standing in
the way and his threats are far from obvious.} Nbd7 13. Rc1 ({Another possible
setup is} 13. Qe2 Rfe8 14. Rad1 {But White is likely to reach a dead end soon.}
Bf8 15. Nc2 {[%cal Gf2f4]} ({Preparing f2-f4 as} 15. f4 {runs into} e5 16. Nf5
b5) 15... Rad8 16. Ne3 h5 17. f4 g6 18. Qd2 Bc6 19. Qc2 Qb8 20. a4 {Shankland,
S (2656)-Hambleton,A (2446) Edmonton 2015 (1-0, 58)} b5 $5 21. cxb5 axb5 22. a5
b4 23. Ncd5 {The only try to get something out of the position.} exd5 24. Qxc6
dxe4 25. Bh3 Rc8 26. Qa4 Nc5 27. Qa2 Bg7 28. Bxc8 Qxc8 {with great
compensation for the exchange due to the better structure and the control on
d3.}) 13... Rfe8 ({I remember that when preferring this over} 13... Rad8 {
in the game below I was mainly concerned about completing the kingside
development with ...Bf8 so as to meet f2-f4 with ...e6-e5. But I soon found
out that changing the move order could lead to problems after} 14. Nd5 $1 exd5
15. cxd5 Qb8 16. Nf5 $1 {This is the point: Black is not in time for ...Bf8
and ...g6.} Rfe8 17. g4 {[%csl Rb7] with strong initiative for the piece. The
b7-bishop is a mere spectator.}) 14. Rc2 (14. Nd5 {is entirely sound but
should lead to approximate equality:} exd5 15. cxd5 Qb8 16. Nc6 (16. Nf5 {
is inoffensive now:} Bf8 17. g4 g6 $17) 16... Bxc6 17. dxc6 {Sulava,N (2478)
-Spraggett,K (2585) Metz 2005 (½-½, 61)} Ne5 $1 {Blocking the e4-pawn at the
cost of returning the piece.} 18. c7 (18. f4 Qc7 19. fxe5 dxe5 20. Qe2 Bc5+ {
Preparing to win the c6-pawn.} 21. Kh1 a5 22. a3 Rad8 23. Red1 Rxd1+ 24. Qxd1
Re6 25. Qc2 $6 Ng4 $1) 18... Qa7 19. f4 Rac8 20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Bxe5 $1 {
The only way to avoid the worst of it.} Bc5+ 22. Rxc5 bxc5 23. Bxf6 gxf6 24.
Qg4+ Kh8 25. Qh4 c4+ 26. Kf1 Qd4 {White surely has compensation for the
exchange but his attack is most likely to yield into a perpetual check only:}
27. Bh3 Rxc7 28. Bf5 Kg7 29. Qxh7+ Kf8 30. Qh6+ Ke7 31. e5 cxb3 $5 32. Qxf6+ {
with a perpetual check, as if} Kf8 33. axb3 Rc3 34. Re2 Qd5 {White needs look
for his king's safety, too.}) ({Or if} 14. f4 Rad8 15. Qe2 (15. f5 {as in
Dorfman,J (2595)-Rastenis,G (2200) Moscow 1979 (½-½, 30) is simplest parried
with} Bf8 {[%csl Ge5] keeping the control of e5.}) 15... Bf8 16. h3 Qb8 17. Nc2
g6 18. Rcd1 {Sunye Neto,J (2475)-Segal,A Brasilia 1982 (1-0, 63)} h5 $5 {
[%cal Gf8g7,Gg7h6] followed by either ...Bh6 or ...Bg7.}) 14... Bf8 15. f4 Rad8
16. Rd2 Qb8 17. Bf3 {[%cal Ge4e5] This is the regrouping my opponent had in
mind. His main threat is e4-e5, leaving my knights short of good squares.} h5
