[PlyCount "64"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. Re1 Be7 8. e4 d6
9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7 11. Be3 O-O 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. f4 Rac8 14. f5 e5 15. Nb3
$1 {White tries to keep the position static. He needs to prevent the freeing ..
.b6-b5 (which could result into a later ...d6-d5) and prepare his kingside
attack. There are some technical problems regarding the latter issue as he
needs to control g5 after a knight retreat, otherwise Black would play ...Qd8
and ...Bg5. The only drawback of the last move is that the knight is far from
c6, making Nd5 (followed by a knight exchange) less dangerous for Black.} h6 $5
$146 {After thourough analysis I have come to the conclusion that this
untested move is the safest. Black simply takes measures against the pawn
attack, which is the highest priority for the time being.} (15... Rfe8 {
could lead to similar play but I do not like the fact that after} 16. Nd5 (16.
Nd2 {Janssen,R (2492)-Gurevich,V (2452) Germany 2006 (1-0, 35) allows} b5 $5
17. cxb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 Qb8 19. Rxc8 Rxc8 {with active queenside play and
prospects of opening the centre with ...d6-d5. Compare with the similar line
below.}) 16... Nxd5 17. cxd5 Qb8 {the rook exchanges along the c-file would
actually cost Black a tempo, Duppel,M (2446)-Rau,H (2297) Schwaebisch Gmuend
2002 (½-½, 38) True, this may be not essential, but the suggested move
avoids it.}) 16. h4 {The most flexible way of preparing the attack. In some
cases the king could go to h3 before g3-g4, in order to keep h4 defended.} (16.
g4 Nh7 {[%cal Gc7d8,Ge7g5] followed by ...Qd8 and ..Bg5 is very comfortable
for Black.}) (16. Nd2 {can be answered in familiar way:} b5 17. cxb5 axb5 18.
Nxb5 Qb8 19. a4 (19. Nc3 Nc5 20. Bxc5 Rxc5 21. Kh1 Rfc8 22. Nb3 R5c7 23. Qf3
Bd8 {with a perfect regrouping for the counterattack.}) 19... Rxc1 20. Qxc1 Rc8
21. Qd1 Nc5 22. Bxc5 Rxc5 {With excellent compensation. In both lines the
missing dark-squared bishop is likely to cause White some problems.}) (16. a4 {
[%csl Rb3] weakens the b3-knight allowing} Qxc4 $5 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. Rxc4 Bxc4 {
with approximate material equality and a a better structure for Black. One
important point is that g3-g4 not only fails to threaten anything immediate,
but also loses the g4-pawn due to the hanging knight.}) (16. Bf2 Qb8 $1 ({
In the main line we have} 16... Rfe8 {but here White has} 17. Bf1 {defending
c4 and preventing ...b6-b5. This was made possible after over-defending e4.})
17. Qe2 Bc6 18. Bf1 Bd8 $5 {[%cal Gd8b6] Preparing to exchange the passive
bishop via b6.} 19. a4 (19. h4 b5 20. cxb5 axb5 21. Nxb5 Bb6 $44 {offers Black
good play on dark squares.}) 19... Nc5 $1 {The a4-pawn is hanging.} 20. Nxc5
bxc5 {[%csl Gg8][%cal Gb8b1] with counterplay along the b-file and a safe
kingside position.}) (16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. cxd5 {leads to approximate equality:}
Qb8 18. h4 Rxc1 19. Nxc1 Rc8 20. Bf3 a5 21. Bf2 Ba6 22. g4 Qc7 {and Black has
good counterplay already.}) 16... Rfe8 $5 {[%cal Gc7c4] By defending the
bishop Black creates the potential threat of taking the c4-pawn.} (16... Bc6 $5
{is also possible:} 17. Bf2 Qb8 18. a4 h5 $5 19. Bf3 Nc5 ({Other possibilities
are} 19... g6 20. Nd2 Nc5 21. Qc2 b5 {and}) (19... b5 20. cxb5 axb5 21. Na5 Ba8
22. axb5 Bd8 23. b4 Bb6) 20. Nxc5 bxc5 $132) 17. Bf2 {The most consistent
continuation.} (17. a4 Qxc4 $1 18. Nd5 Qxa4 $1 {Possible only because the
bishop is defended.} 19. Rxc8 Bxc8 20. Nxe7+ Rxe7 21. Qxd6 Re8 $17) (17. Nd5
Qd8 $5 {leads to a familiar picture.}) (17. g4 {is a bit premature:} Nh7 (17...
Qxc4 18. g5 {offers White an attack.}) 18. Nd5 (18. Bf2 Qd8 $1) 18... Bxd5 19.
cxd5 Qd8 20. Rxc8 Qxc8 21. Qe2 Bxh4 22. Rc1 Qb7 23. Rc6 Bg5 24. Bf2 Nhf6 $13 {
White's rook's activity compensates for the pawn and for Black's stability on
dark squares. He should, however, refrain from} 25. Rxd6 $2 {due to} Rc8 $15 {
with initiative.}) ({Preparing g4 with} 17. Bf3 $5 {[%cal Gg3g4] is best
answered with} b5 $1 ({The same answer as in the main line does not work here,
because of the slight difference in the white bishops' placement:} 17... Qxc4
18. g4 Qc7 19. g5 hxg5 20. hxg5 Nh7 21. g6 fxg6 22. fxg6 Nhf8 23. Bg4 Qd8 24.
Qf3 {With the second rank and the h-file available for the enemy rooks, Black
has to prefent Qf7 with the passive} Bf6 $16) 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Nxb5 Qb8 20.
Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Nc3 d5 $1 {The second thematic break.} 22. exd5 (22. Nxd5 Bxd5
23. exd5 e4 24. Bf2 Bc5 25. Nxc5 Nxc5 $17) 22... Bb4 {with excellent
counterplay in the centre.}) 17... Qxc4 ({Black can also try} 17... h5 {
with interesting complications after} 18. Bf3 Qxc4 19. Bxh5 Nxh5 20. Qxh5 Qb4
21. Qd1 d5 22. Nxd5 Rxc1 23. Nxc1 Bxd5 24. Qxd5 Nf6 25. Qb3 Rc8 {The chronical
weakness on e4 and Black's overall activity compensate for the pawn.}) 18. g4 {
White uses the time wasted by the black queen for launchig his attack. But
Black has enough defensive resources:} Qc7 19. g5 hxg5 20. hxg5 Nh7 21. g6 fxg6
22. fxg6 Nhf8 23. Bh3 Qd8 24. Qf3 Bg5 (24... Bh4 $5 {also works:} 25. Bxh4 Qxh4
26. Bxd7 Nxd7 27. Qf7+ Kh8 28. Qxd7 Qg3+ {with a perpetual.}) 25. Qf7+ Kh8 26.
Rcd1 Qe7 27. Qxe7 Bxe7 28. Bf5 {White has compensation for the pawn due to his
space advantage, but Black can avoid mate along the h-file, keeping the
balance even.} Kg8 29. Rd3 Nf6 30. Bxb6 (30. Bxc8 Rxc8 31. Bxb6 Nxg6 $15 {
offers Black fantastic compensation for the exchange.}) (30. Rh3 Bd8 31. Kg2
Ne6 32. Bg3 Kf8 $13) 30... Rc6 31. Bf2 (31. Be3 Rxc3 $5) 31... Bd8 32. Red1 Bc7
{Black does not experience problems and can start his counterplay with ...Ne6.}
*

