1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. Re1 Be7 8. e4 d6
9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7 11. Be3 O-O 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. f4 Rac8 14. g4 {This move
yields White's attack a wider character than in the previous lines.} Nc5 {
Forcing the bishop to abandon the defence of the c1-rook, thus turning Nd5
inoffensive.} 15. Bf2 g6 {The typical answer, peparing to meet g4-g5 with ...
Nh5.} 16. b4 ({If} 16. Bg3 {as in Ulybin,M (2587)-Praveen Kumar,C (2338) New
Delhi 2012 (1-0, 41) Black can neutralize the threat e4-e5 with} h6 {followed
by the usual regrouping with ...Rfe8 and ...Bf8.}) (16. e5 dxe5 17. fxe5 Nfd7
18. b4 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Nb7 $11) ({For} 16. f5 {[%emt 0:00:06] see Line}) 16...
Ncd7 17. g5 {There are many alternatives to this.} (17. f5 gxf5 18. exf5 (18.
gxf5 e5 19. Nde2 Kh8 {Not only neutralizing White's chances for an attack, but
also preparing his own counterattack along the g-file as the g2-bishop is
vulnerable.} 20. Nd5 Nxd5 21. exd5 Rg8 22. Ng3 Bg5 23. Rc3 Nf6 24. c5 bxc5 25.
bxc5 dxc5 26. d6 Qa5 27. Bxb7 Qxc3 28. Bxc8 Rxc8 29. Qb3 Qxb3 30. axb3 Bf4 {
with roughly equal chances in Jumabayev,R (2613)-Marin,M (2576) Almaty (blitz)
2016 (1-0, 50)}) 18... Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qb7+ 20. Qf3 (20. Kg1 Ne5 21. g5 Nfg4 22.
f6 Rxc4 $5 23. fxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Gf7f6] followed by ...f7-f6 soon, with a very
dangerous combined attack.}) 20... Qxf3+ 21. Kxf3 Ne5+ $17 {Lobron,E-Marin,M
World Chess Network (rapid) 2001 (0-1, 24)}) (17. Nb3 {takes measures against .
..e6-e5 but is too passive to cause problems.} Qb8 18. Qe2 (18. e5 dxe5 19.
Bxb7 Qxb7 20. fxe5 Nxe5 21. Rxe5 Rxc4 22. h3 Rxb4 {with three pawns for the
piece and very active play.}) {Hutters,T-Marin,M World Chess Network (rapid)
2001 (0-1, 47)} 18... d5 19. e5 Bxb4 20. exf6 Rxc4 21. Bd4 Qxf4 {once again
with excellent compensation for the piece.}) (17. Bf3 {[%cal Gg4g5] threatens
g4-g5, but things will not get that far:} e5 $1 18. Nd5 Qd8 19. Ne2 Bxd5 {
Missing White's saving resource mentioned below.} (19... Nxd5 $1 20. exd5 exf4
21. Nxf4 Ne5 22. Re4 Bg5 $15) 20. exd5 e4 21. Bg2 (21. Nd4 $1 {would have led
to huge complications resulting into approximately equal chances:} exf3 22. Nc6
Rxc6 23. dxc6 Nxg4 24. c7 Qxc7 25. Rxe7 Qc6 26. Rc3 Nxf2 27. Kxf2 Nf6 28. Qxf3
d5 $11 {with entirely adequate compensation for the exchange due to the weak
white king.}) 21... Nxg4 22. Bxe4 Nxf2 23. Kxf2 b5 24. cxb5 Bh4+ 25. Ng3 Qb6+
26. Kg2 Qxb5 $17 {Solovyov,V-Marin, M St Petersburg (rapid) 2017 (0-1, 35)}) (
17. b5 $5 {is a very interesting attempt to get the initiative on the light
squares even at the cost of a pawn.} e5 18. Nc6 ({More consistent than} 18.
bxa6 Bxa6 19. Ndb5 Qd8 20. f5 Ne8 21. Ne2 Nc5 22. Ng3 Ra8 {with the better
structure and a normal position for Black in Stella,A (2423)-Aroshidze,L (2535)
Figueres 2015 (0-1, 56).}) 18... Bxc6 19. bxc6 Qxc6 20. f5 h6 {Slowing down
White's attack.} 21. h4 Bd8 {Inhibiting g4-g5.} 22. Bf3 (22. g5 hxg5 23. hxg5
Nh7 24. Nd5 Bxg5) 22... Qb7 23. Qxd6 (23. Be3 Nh7 24. Bxh6 Bxh4 $132) 23...
Rxc4 24. fxg6 (24. g5 hxg5 25. hxg5 Nh7 26. fxg6 Nxg5 27. gxf7+ Rxf7 $15) 24...
Rc6 25. gxf7+ Rxf7 26. Qd3 Nxg4 27. Bxg4 Rg6 $132) 17... Nh5 18. Qg4 Nxf4 {
A thematic move simplifying and freeing Black's position.} (18... Rfe8 19. Nce2
Bf8 $13) (18... Qd8 19. Nd5 $5 exd5 20. exd5 Nxf4 21. Qxf4 Ne5 22. h4 Nd3 23.
Qe3 Nxc1 24. Qxe7 Qxe7 25. Rxe7 Ba8 26. Nc6 {Harutjunyan,G (2441)-Soltanici,R 
(2421) Khmelnitsky 2008 (1-0, 35)} b5 $11) 19. Qxf4 e5 20. Qg3 ({More active
than} 20. Qd2 exd4 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. exd5 Qd8 23. h4 h6 $15) 20... exd4 21. Nd5
Bxd5 22. exd5 Rfe8 ({Here, too} 22... Qd8 $5 23. h4 h6 24. gxh6 Kh7 {is
possible.}) 23. Bxd4 Bf8 24. Bh3 (24. Rxe8 Rxe8 25. c5 {is parried with} bxc5
26. bxc5 Qa7 $1) 24... Bg7 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. Rf1 Rcd8 27. Bxd7 Qxd7 $11 {
Rogozenko,D-Marin,M World Chess Network (rapid) 2001 (0-1, 39)} *

