19... Rfe8 20. b4 (20. g5 Nfe4 21. f6 Nxg5 $132 {Fodor,T (2452)-Arun,K (2289)
Chotowa 2010 (1-0, 41)}) 20... Ncd7 21. g5 Nh5 22. f6 Bf8 23. Rxe8 {½-½
Hernandez Fernandez,N (2251)-Depasse,J (2321) ICCF email 2015}) 17. gxf5 (17.
exf5 {offers Black good counterplay in the centre:} Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qb7+ 19. Kg1
(19. Qf3 Qxf3+ 20. Kxf3 Nd3 21. fxe6 Rxc4 $19) 19... Nfe4 20. Nxe4 Nxe4 21. Qf3
d5 22. Be3 b5 23. cxd5 Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Qxd5 $11) 17... e5 18. Nc2 (18. Nb3 Kh8
19. Bf3 (19. Nxc5 bxc5) 19... Ne8 {Preparing to activate the bishop.} 20. Nd5 (
20. Be3 Rg8+ 21. Kh1 Bg5 $15) 20... Bxd5 21. Qxd5 Qd8 $1 $15 {It looks like
black is planning to retire his whole army on the back rank . In reality, this
is the shortest way to exchange the bishops.} 22. Rc2 Bh4 23. Bg3 b5 $1 {
with initiative for Black already, Sammalvuo,T (2433)-Marin,M (2551)
Gothenburg 2002 (0-1, 36).}) 18... Kh8 {A familiar plan.} 19. Kh1 Rg8 20. Bf3
b5 21. Nd5 {The only way to keep things under control.} (21. cxb5 axb5 22. Qe2
(22. b4 Nd3 $1 $17) (22. Nxb5 Ncxe4 $3 $19) 22... Qd7 $13 23. Nb4 Na4 (23... d5
{also seems to be working:} 24. Nbxd5 Ncxe4 25. Nxe4 Bxd5 26. Nxf6 Bxf6 27.
Rcd1 Bxf3+ 28. Qxf3 Qe7 $11) 24. Nxa4 (24. Nxb5 {allows some nice tactics:}
Rxc1 25. Rxc1 Nxe4 $1 26. Bxe4 Qxb5 $3) 24... bxa4 $132 {with excellent
counterplay.}) 21... Nxd5 (21... Qd7 $5 $36 {was possible as after} 22. Nxe7
Qxe7 23. Bh4 {Black has} Nfxe4 $1 {and once again the vulnerability of his
king costs White dearly.}) 22. cxd5 (22. exd5 bxc4 $132) 22... Na4 $5 (22...
Bg5 $5 23. Ne3 Qa5 24. a3 Qa4 25. Qxa4 Nxa4 26. b4 $13) 23. Ne3 (23. b3 Nc3 24.
Qd2 Nxa2 $17) (23. Nb4 Nxb2 24. Qd2 Nc4 $17) 23... Nxb2 24. Qd2 Nc4 25. Nxc4
bxc4 26. Rc3 Bg5 27. Qc2 a5 28. Rb1 $44 {With just enough compensation for the
pawn in Epishin,V (2657)-Marin,M (2548) Koszalin 1999 (1/2, 28)} *

